FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - BULGARIA (03): (BURGAS) BOVINE
*****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Mon 10 Jan 2011
Source: The Sofia Echo [edited]
<http://www.sofiaecho.com/2011/01/10/1022278_fmd-spreads-in-bulgaria-with-37-new-confirmed-cases>


Bulgarian authorities have confirmed the spread of foot and mouth
disease (FMD) in the Burgas village of Kosti, with 37 domestic
animals reportedly infected, Bulgarian television channel bTV
announced on 10 Jan 2011.

There are other cases of FMD around the village also confirmed,
Yordan Voinov from the national veterinary service told bTV. "This is
most likely an infection in a very early phase, as only one cow from
the entire cattle herd was found to be infected. Investigations
conducted in the villages of Rezovo and Malko Turnovo proved
negative," Voinov said. "By culling the animals and disinfecting the
others, we are hoping to tackle the spread of the virus," he added.

In the course of the past few days, authorities checked 1600 animals
in the Burgas municipality and in regions near Haskovo and Yambol in
the southeast. Of those, 500 animals will be destroyed, according to
Dnevnik daily.

Last week [week of 3 Jan 2010], the regional commissions adopted
emergency measures against the spread of the virus in Haskovo,
Burgas, Varna, and Yambol.

For the 1st time in 45 years, a case of FMD was registered in the
country after a wild boar crossed the border from Turkey near the
village of Kosti. Authorities have started reconstructing the fence
along the border where it had fallen apart, to prevent any other
animals slipping in.

In turn, the European Commission took urgent protection measures on 6
Jan 2011 to increase control measures for FMD already implemented by
the Bulgarian authorities.

The Commission's measures pertain both to high-risk areas (such as
the region of Burgas) and low-risk areas (such as the provinces of
Yambol, Sliven, Shumen, and Varna) and stipulate the rules for the
safe trade of items produced before the restrictions.

The measures include "epidemiological investigation, suspension of
hunting, and a ban on feeding wild animals, placing under official
surveillance holdings keeping animals of susceptible species,
inspection by an official veterinarian of all wild animals shot or
found dead," the report said.

FMD is a highly contagious and sometimes fatal viral disease of
cloven-hoofed animals, including domestic animals such as cattle,
water buffalo, sheep, goats, and pigs, as well as antelope, bison,
and other wild bovids, and deer.

