[It is highly doubtful if "reconstructing the fence along the border
where it had fallen apart" will indeed "prevent any other animals
slipping in"; certainly such fence does not exclude the spread of the
virus. If the virus has indeed been circulating within the wild boar
population of neighbouring Turkish Thrace, its potential to penetrate
the border into Bulgaria, either on foot (and mouth...) or by air, is
realistic. An intact, thick security fence along the Israeli-Lebanese
border, did not prevent the spread of infection into wild boars
within Israel's territory in 1992. A report on surveillance in wild
boars in northern Israel was included in ProMED-mail archive no
20070517.1571; at least in one case (in the village Mevo Hamma, Golan
Heights), the virus activity in boar seemed to have taken place some
time before outbreaks in domestic livestock were recorded.

The circulation of FMDV serotype O in wild boars in Thrace, bordering
Bulgaria, should not be overly surprising. On 28 Feb 2007, Turkey
notified the OIE on an outbreak of FMD in cattle in Kirklareli
(Armagan, Armagan, Merkez). The reported epidemiology was "contact
with an infected boar" (see ProMED-mail 20070301.0726). This was the
background to the following commentary by ProMED-mail's moderator PC:
"The location of the outbreak in the Marmara region of Turkey, just
south of the Bulgarian border, can be seen by accessing the full OIE
report. This outbreak is in the same general region as the January
[2007] outbreak in Edirne. The epidemiology of the outbreak should
serve as a reminder that exposure to wild boar, a mode of
introduction that has been frequently associated with classical swine
fever, can also serve to introduce other disease agents."

Since porcines are not regarded as effective carriers of FMDV, the
source of their infection should be sought in a more effective
carrier animal. Sheep may be proposed as plausible candidates; see
also commentary in ProMED-mail 20070508.1480.

A thorough epidemiological surveillance in Thrace, with sheep flocks
high on the listed targets, deserves to be considered. An official
confirmation of FMDV spreading to cattle in Bulgaria, and the
serotyping/genotyping results of the samples submitted to the WRLFMD
at Pirbright, are anticipated. - Mod.AS

Maps of Bulgaria are available at <http://healthmap.org/r/0lV6> and
<http://www.ant-est.ru/bulgaria/bulgaria.gif>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
